The Convenient Chips is a solemn poetic form intended to teach a moral lesson concerning Thomod, originating in The Meandering Confederacy. The rules of the form are applied by poets to produce individual poems which can be recited. The poem is two nine-line stanzas. Each line has five feet with a tone pattern of even-even-uneven. The second line of each stanza uses the same placement of allusions as the first line.

The Strategic Number of Orbs is a solemn poetic form concerning religion, originating in The Meandering Confederacy. The form guides poets during improvised performances. The poem is divided into a line and two quintains. The Strategic Number of Orbs is always written from the perspective of a historical figure. Every line of the poem has a medial caesura. musical_form.description: The Fortuitous Suitor is a form of music used for entertainment originating in The Rack of Murdering. The form guides musicians during improvised performances. Two singers recite any composition of The Beige Desserts. The entire performance should be graceful and is very slow, and it is to be in whispered undertones. The melody has mid-length phrases throughout the form. Only one pitch is ever played at a time. It is performed using the kulet scale. Throughout, when possible, performers are to glide from note to note, use mordents and match notes and syllables. [B]Each singer always does the main melody. [B]The Fortuitous Suitor has a well-defined multi-passage structure: a lengthy first theme, an exposition of the first theme, a lengthy second theme, an exposition of the second theme, a bridge-passage and a synthesis of previous passages. [B]In the first theme, each of the singers' voices ranges from the low register to the middle register. The passage is performed in free rhythm. [B]In the first exposition, each of the singers' voices stays in the high register. The passage is performed in the lakish rhythm. [B]In the second theme, each of the singers' voices ranges from the low register to the middle register. The passage is performed in the gostang rhythm. [B]In the second exposition, each of the singers' voices stays in the middle register. The passage is performed in free rhythm. [B]In the bridge-passage, each of the singers' voices ranges from the low register to the middle register. The passage is performed in the libash rhythm. [B]In the synthesis, each of the singers' voices stays in the high register. The passage is performed in the nel rhythm. [B]Scales are constructed from sixteen notes dividing the octave. In quartertones, their spacing is roughly 1-xx-x-x-xx-xxxx-xx-x-xxO, where 1 is the tonic, O marks the octave and x marks other notes. The tonic note is a fixed tone passed from teacher to student. After a scale is constructed, notes are named according to degree. The names are emar (spoken em), izeg (iz), bemong (be), gost (go), ontak (ont), tosid (to) and feb (fe). [B]The kulet heptatonic scale is constructed by selection of degrees from the fundamental scale. The degrees selected are the 1st, the 3rd, the 5th, the 8th, the 9th, the 11th and the 13th. [B]The rhythm system is fundamentally polyrhythmic. There are always multiple rhythm lines, and each of their bars is played over the same period of time, regardless of the number of beats. The rhythm lines are thought of as one, without a primary-subordinate relationship, though individual lines can be named. [B]The lakish rhythm is made from two patterns: the ibruk and the thatthil. As stated above, they are to be played in polyrhythm. [B]The ibruk rhythm is a single line with two beats. The beats are named ermis (spoken erm) and thoth (tho). The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x - | [B]where x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The thatthil rhythm is a single line with thirty-two beats divided into four bars in a 8-7-7-10 pattern. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x x ! x x x x x | - - - x - x - | x x X x x - - | - - - - - - - - - x | [B]where ! marks the primary accent, X marks an accented beat, x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The gostang rhythm is a single line with thirty-two beats divided into four bars in a 3-9-7-13 pattern. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x X x | - x - x X - - - - | x - - x x X - | - x - - - - x - - - x X - | [B]where X marks an accented beat, x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The libash rhythm is a single line with twenty beats divided into four bars in a 5-5-5-5 pattern. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x - - X x | x x x ! - | - X x - x | x X x x x | [B]where ! marks the primary accent, X marks an accented beat, x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The nel rhythm is made from two patterns: the ibruk (considered the primary) and the thatthil. As stated above, they are to be played in polyrhythm.

The Zephyr of Berries is a form of music used to commemorate important events originating in The Rack of Murdering. The rules of the form are applied by composers to produce individual pieces of music which can be performed. The music is played on a geshud, a thosbut and a damol. The musical voices bring melody, counterpoint and rhythm. The melody has long phrases, while the counterpoint has short phrases throughout the form. The music repeats for as long as necessary. It is performed using the anam scale. Throughout, when possible, composers and performers are to make trills and play rapid runs. [B]The geshud always should be delicate. [B]The thosbut always should stress the rhythm. [B]The damol always should perform expressively. [B]The Zephyr of Berries has a well-defined multi-passage structure: a passage and an additional lengthy passage possibly all repeated and a coda. [B]The second simple passage is voiced by the melody of the damol and the counterpoint of the geshud. The passage accelerates as it proceeds, and it is to be moderately soft. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x X x | - x - x X - - - - | x - - x x X - | - x - - - - x - - - x X - | [B]where X marks an accented beat, x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x - | [B]where x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The roder rhythm is made from two patterns: the libash (considered the primary) and the gostang. As stated above, they are to be played in polyrhythm. [B]The libash rhythm is a single line with twenty beats divided into four bars in a 5-5-5-5 pattern. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x - - X x | x x x ! - | - X x - x | x X x x x | [B]where ! marks the primary accent, X marks an accented beat, x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x x ! x x x x x | - - - x - x - | x x X x x - - | - - - - - - - - - x | [B]where ! marks the primary accent, X marks an accented beat, x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar.

The Music of Poetry is a devotional form of music originating in The Buff Satins. The form guides musicians during improvised performances. A chanter recites nonsensical words and sounds. The entire performance is to start loud then be immediately soft. The melody has mid-length phrases throughout the form. Only one pitch is ever played at a time. It is performed using the adi scale and in the fidale rhythm. Throughout, when possible, performers are to use mordents, locally improvise and play arpeggios. From beginning to end, when improvising, artists should always include a falling melody pattern with glides and grace notes, sometimes include a rising melody pattern with sharpened second degree as well as grace notes and staccato and often include a rising-falling melody pattern with flattened sixth degree on the rise as well as glides, trills and staccato. [B]The chanter always does the main melody. [B]The Music of Poetry has a well-defined multi-passage structure: an introduction, three to five unrelated passages and a coda. [B]The introduction should feel agitated and is extremely fast. The chanter's voice stays in the middle register. [B]Each of the simple passages should be broad and is at a walking pace. The chanter's voice stays in the high register. [B]The coda should bring a sense of motion and is moderately fast. The chanter's voice ranges from the middle register to the high register. [B]Scales are constructed from twenty-four notes spaced evenly throughout the octave. The tonic note is fixed only at the time of performance. Preferred notes in the fundamental scale are named. The names are fathinu (spoken fa, 2nd), thili (thi, 3rd), fomire (fo, 9th), fela (fe, 10th), aweme (aw, 13th), yaniye (ya, 14th), atho (ath, 15th), datome (da, 17th), lari (la, 18th), aratha (ar, 19th), imeri (im, 23rd) and thuna (thu, 24th). [B]The adi hexatonic scale is constructed by selection of degrees from the fundamental scale. The degrees selected are the 1st, the 5th, the 9th, the 16th, the 17th and the 20th. [B]The rhythm system is fundamentally polyrhythmic. There are always multiple rhythm lines, and each of their bars is played over the same period of time, regardless of the number of beats. The rhythm lines are thought of as one, without a primary-subordinate relationship, though individual lines can be named. [B]The fidale rhythm is a single line with twenty-nine beats divided into three bars in a 11-7-11 pattern. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x - - x - X - - - x x | - x - - - - - | X - x x x x x - x x - | [B]where X marks an accented beat, x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar.

The Lace of Playing is a form of music used during marches and military engagements originating in The Buff Satins. The rules of the form are applied by composers to produce individual pieces of music which can be performed. The music is played on a awiyi and a irumo. The musical voices bring melody with harmony. The entire performance should feel mysterious and is at a free tempo. The melody has long phrases throughout the form. Only one pitch is ever played at a time. It is performed using the datha scale and in the arazi rhythm. [B]The irumo always does the main melody. [B]The Lace of Playing has a well-defined multi-passage structure: a theme, an exposition of the theme and a recapitulation of the theme. [B]The theme is voiced by the melody of the irumo and the harmony of the awiyi. The passage is to become softer and softer. The irumo ranges from the wispy middle register to the raucous high register and the awiyi ranges from the middle register to the high register. The passage should be composed and performed using arpeggios. [B]The exposition is voiced by the melody of the awiyi and the melody of the irumo. The passage is to be in whispered undertones. The awiyi ranges from the middle register to the high register and the irumo ranges from the watery low register to the wispy middle register. The passage should be composed and performed using trills. [B]The recapitulation is voiced by the melody of the awiyi and the melody of the irumo. The passage is to be in whispered undertones. The awiyi covers its entire range from the rich low register to the dark high register and the irumo ranges from the watery low register to the wispy middle register. [B]Scales are constructed from twenty-four notes spaced evenly throughout the octave. The tonic note is fixed only at the time of performance. Preferred notes in the fundamental scale are named. The rhythm lines are thought of as one, without a primary-subordinate relationship, though individual lines can be named. [B]The arazi rhythm is a single line with two beats. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x x | [B]where x is a beat and | indicates a bar.

The Velvety Music is a form of music used for entertainment originating in The Buff Satins. The rules of the form are applied by composers to produce individual pieces of music which can be performed. Three singers recite any composition of The Grand Boot while the music is played on a cona and a awiyi. The musical voices join in melody and counterpoint, harmony and rhythm. The entire performance is to become softer and softer. The melody and counterpoint both have phrases of varied length throughout the form. It is performed using the eyo scale and in the cenopu rhythm. Throughout, when possible, composers and performers are to alternate tension and repose and spread syllables over many notes. [B]Each singer always should feel tender. [B]The cona always should feel mysterious. The voice uses its entire range from the dull low register to the flat high register. [B]The awiyi always should feel mournful. [B]The Velvety Music has a well-defined multi-passage structure: a chorus and a verse all repeated two times, a bridge-passage and a lengthy chorus and a lengthy verse. [B]The first chorus is voiced by the melody of the singers and the harmony of the awiyi. The passage slows and broadens. [B]The first verse is voiced by the melody of the awiyi and the rhythm of the singers. The passage is at a hurried pace. The awiyi stays in the rich low register and each of the singers' voices ranges from the low register to the middle register. This passage typically has some sparse chords. [B]The bridge-passage is voiced by the melody of the cona and the rhythm of the singers. The passage is very fast. The cona covers its entire range from the dull low register to the flat high register and each of the singers' voices ranges from the low register to the middle register. Only one pitch is ever played at a time in this passage. [B]The second chorus is voiced by the melody of the singers. The passage is moderately paced. Each of the singers' voices covers its entire range. Only one pitch is ever played at a time in this passage. [B]The second verse is voiced by the melody of the singers, the melody of the awiyi and the counterpoint of the cona. The passage moves more quickly than the last passage. Each of the singers' voices stays in the low register, the awiyi ranges from the rich low register to the dark middle register and the cona covers its entire range from the dull low register to the flat high register. The rhythm lines are thought of as one, without a primary-subordinate relationship, though individual lines can be named. [B]The cenopu rhythm is a single line with four beats. The beats are named ele (spoken el), timafi (ti), emu (em) and upe (up). The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| X x x x | [B]where X marks an accented beat, x is a beat and | indicates a bar.

The Confident Knot is a devotional form of music directed toward the worship of Obin originating in The Empire of Gullies. The form guides musicians during improvised performances. The rhythm lines are thought of as one, without a primary-subordinate relationship, though individual lines can be named. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x - | x - | x x | - x | x x | x x | x - | x - | [B]where x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar.

The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| - X - x x x | X x - x x x | x x - X x x | x X x - x x | - - - - - x | [B]where X marks an accented beat, x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The lari rhythm is a single line with twenty-two beats divided into two bars in a 9-13 pattern. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x - - - - - - x - | - x - - - - - X x - - - - | [B]where X marks an accented beat, x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The tarathe rhythm is made from two patterns: the fomire and the datome. The patterns are to be played over the same period of time, concluding together regardless of beat number.

The Tones of Saffron is a devotional form of music originating in The Vault of Spiraling. The form guides musicians during improvised performances. A chanter recites The True Quiescent Gloss while the music is played on one to two shosel and a romab. The musical voices bring melody, counterpoint and rhythm. The entire performance should be triumphant. The melody has long phrases, while the counterpoint has phrases of varied length throughout the form. Only one pitch is ever played at a time. The music repeats for as long as necessary. It is performed in the agek rhythm. Throughout, when possible, performers are to use grace notes and add fills. [B]The chanter always does the counterpoint melody. The voice ranges from the low register to the middle register. [B]Each shosel always does the main melody. The voice uses its entire range from the crisp low register to the heavy high register. [B]The romab always provides the rhythm. [B]The Tones of Saffron has a simple structure: three to four unrelated passages. [B]Each of the simple passages slows and broadens, and it is to be moderately loud. Each passage is performed using the feb scale. [B]Scales are constructed from twelve notes spaced evenly throughout the octave. The tonic note is fixed only at the time of performance. Every note is named. The names are thoth (spoken tho), thatthil (tha), gostang (go), libash (li), lakish (la), asdos (as), roder (ro), nel (ne), biban (bi), ugog (ug), ish (ish) and olmul (ol). [B]The feb hexatonic scale is thought of as two disjoint chords spanning a tritone and a perfect fourth. These chords are named tosid and ustos. [B]The tosid tetrachord is the 1st, the 4th, the 5th and the 7th degrees of the semitone octave scale. [B]The ustos trichord is the 8th, the 9th and the 13th (completing the octave) degrees of the semitone octave scale. [B]The rhythm system is fundamentally polyrhythmic. There are always multiple rhythm lines, and each of their bars is played over the same period of time, regardless of the number of beats. The rhythm lines are thought of as one, without a primary-subordinate relationship, though individual lines can be named. [B]The rhythm system is fundamentally polymetric. There are always multiple rhythm lines, and the beats are always played together, even if one rhythm line completes (and then repeats) before the other is finished. The rhythm lines are thought of as one, without a primary-subordinate relationship, though individual lines can be named. [B]The agek rhythm is a single line with two beats. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| - x | [B]where x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar.

The Pantomime of Sheens is a form of music used during marches and military engagements originating in The Vault of Spiraling. The form guides musicians during improvised performances. A chanter recites nonsensical words and sounds. The melody has mid-length phrases throughout the form. Only one pitch is ever played at a time. It is performed using the izeg scale. Throughout, when possible, performers are to glide from note to note. [B]The chanter always does the main melody. [B]The Pantomime of Sheens has a well-defined multi-passage structure: a lengthy theme, a bridge-passage and one to two series of variations on the theme possibly all repeated. [B]The theme should be made with feeling and is at a walking pace, and it is to fade into silence. The chanter's voice covers its entire range. The passage is performed in the enor rhythm. [B]The bridge-passage should be made expressively and is at a walking pace, and it is to start loud then be immediately soft. The chanter's voice stays in the low register. The passage is performed in the okag rhythm. [B]Each of the series of variations should bring a sense of motion and is very fast, and it is to start loud then be immediately soft. The chanter's voice stays in the low register. Each passage is performed in the nokzam rhythm. [B]Scales are constructed from twelve notes spaced evenly throughout the octave. The tonic note is fixed only at the time of performance. Every note is named. The names are thoth (spoken tho), thatthil (tha), gostang (go), libash (li), lakish (la), asdos (as), roder (ro), nel (ne), biban (bi), ugog (ug), ish (ish) and olmul (ol). [B]The izeg hexatonic scale is thought of as two disjoint chords spanning a tritone and a perfect fourth. These chords are named gost and ustos. [B]The gost tetrachord is the 1st, the 4th, the 6th and the 7th degrees of the semitone octave scale. [B]The ustos trichord is the 8th, the 9th and the 13th (completing the octave) degrees of the semitone octave scale. [B]The rhythm system is fundamentally polyrhythmic. There are always multiple rhythm lines, and each of their bars is played over the same period of time, regardless of the number of beats. The rhythm lines are thought of as one, without a primary-subordinate relationship, though individual lines can be named. [B]The rhythm system is fundamentally polymetric. There are always multiple rhythm lines, and the beats are always played together, even if one rhythm line completes (and then repeats) before the other is finished. The rhythm lines are thought of as one, without a primary-subordinate relationship, though individual lines can be named. [B]The enor rhythm is made from two patterns: the uvel and the etag. As stated above, they are to be played in polyrhythm. [B]The uvel rhythm is a single line with two beats. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x x | [B]where x is a beat and | indicates a bar. [B]The etag rhythm is a single line with thirty-two beats divided into five bars in a 6-5-7-8-6 pattern. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x x x x x x | x - x - - | x x - - - - - | x x - x - - - - | x - - x - - | [B]where x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The okag rhythm is made from three patterns: the erong, the ucat and the dolush. As stated above, they are to be played in polyrhythm. [B]The erong rhythm is a single line with two beats. The beats are named osed (spoken os) and lanlar (la). The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x x | [B]where x is a beat and | indicates a bar. [B]The ucat rhythm is a single line with sixteen beats divided into four bars in a 4-4-4-4 pattern. The beats are named ngarak (spoken nga), enir (en), ugath (ug) and lisig (li). The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| - - x - | x - - - | - - x - | x x x x | [B]where x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The dolush rhythm is a single line with four beats divided into two bars in a 2-2 pattern. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x - | x - | [B]where x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The nokzam rhythm is a single line with two beats. The beats are named emuth (spoken em) and fer (fe). The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x - | [B]where x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar.

The Queen of Fanciness is a form of music used for entertainment originating in The Vault of Spiraling. The form guides musicians during improvised performances. A chanter recites nonsensical words and sounds while the music is played on a deleth. The musical voices bring melody with harmony. The entire performance should bring a sense of motion. The melody has long phrases throughout the form. It is performed using the ermis scale and in the atrid rhythm. [B]The chanter always does the main melody and is to fade into silence. [B]The deleth always does harmony and is to fade into silence. [B]The Queen of Fanciness has the following structure: an introduction and a passage. [B]The introduction is fast. The chanter's voice ranges from the low register to the middle register and the deleth ranges from the muddy low register to the rippling middle register. This passage typically has some sparse chords. [B]The simple passage is slow. The chanter's voice stays in the high register and the deleth ranges from the rippling middle register to the muddy high register. This passage is richly layered with full chords making use of the available range. [B]Scales are constructed from twelve notes spaced evenly throughout the octave. The tonic note is fixed only at the time of performance. Every note is named. The names are thoth (spoken tho), thatthil (tha), gostang (go), libash (li), lakish (la), asdos (as), roder (ro), nel (ne), biban (bi), ugog (ug), ish (ish) and olmul (ol). [B]The ermis pentatonic scale is thought of as two disjoint chords spanning two perfect fourths. These chords are named anam and ustos. [B]The anam trichord is the 1st, the 5th and the 6th degrees of the semitone octave scale. [B]The ustos trichord is the 8th, the 9th and the 13th (completing the octave) degrees of the semitone octave scale. [B]The rhythm system is fundamentally polyrhythmic. There are always multiple rhythm lines, and each of their bars is played over the same period of time, regardless of the number of beats. The rhythm lines are thought of as one, without a primary-subordinate relationship, though individual lines can be named. [B]The rhythm system is fundamentally polymetric. There are always multiple rhythm lines, and the beats are always played together, even if one rhythm line completes (and then repeats) before the other is finished. The rhythm lines are thought of as one, without a primary-subordinate relationship, though individual lines can be named. [B]The atrid rhythm is made from two patterns: the tarmid and the udir. As stated above, they are to be played in polyrhythm. [B]The tarmid rhythm is a single line with thirty-two beats divided into four bars in a 8-8-8-8 pattern. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| - x - - x x - x | - x x x - x - - | - x - x x - x - | - x - - x x - x | [B]where x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The udir rhythm is a single line with twenty-nine beats divided into five bars in a 6-6-5-6-6 pattern. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| - x - - - - | - - x x - x | x - x x x | - x - x x - | x - x x x - | [B]where x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar.

The New Tuft is a devotional form of music directed toward the worship of Duto originating in The Meandering Confederacy. The form guides musicians during improvised performances. The music is played on a nelti, a enthep and one to three ashab. The musical voices join in melody and counterpoint, harmony and rhythm. The melody has mid-length phrases, while the counterpoint has long phrases throughout the form. It is performed without preference for a scale and in the kes rhythm. Throughout, when possible, performers are to glide from note to note, play rapid runs, alternate tension and repose and play arpeggios. [B]The nelti always should be fiery. The voice ranges from the buzzy low register to the raucous middle register. [B]The New Tuft has the following structure: one to two lengthy passages and an additional lengthy passage possibly all repeated. [B]Each of the first simple passages is voiced by the melody of the enthep, the counterpoint of the ashab and the harmony of the nelti. Each passage slows and broadens, and it is to be soft. The enthep ranges from the buzzy low register to the raucous middle register and each of the ashab ranges from the watery middle register to the rippling high register. This passage features only melodic tones and intervals. [B]The second simple passage is voiced by the melody of the ashab, the counterpoint of the enthep and the rhythm of the nelti. The passage is moderately paced, and it is to be loud. Each of the ashab ranges from the muddy low register to the watery middle register and the enthep ranges from the buzzy low register to the raucous middle register. Only one pitch is ever played at a time in this passage. [B]The rhythm system is fundamentally polyrhythmic. There are always multiple rhythm lines, and each of their bars is played over the same period of time, regardless of the number of beats. The rhythm lines are thought of as one, without a primary-subordinate relationship, though individual lines can be named. [B]The kes rhythm is a single line with sixteen beats divided into two bars in a 8-8 pattern. The beats are named suku (spoken su), rorec (ro), musda (mu), uzu (uz), onaf (on), agthreb (ag), kaslal (ka) and seggu (se). The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x x'x x x x'- ! | x - - - x x x X | [B]where ! marks the primary accent, X marks an accented beat, ' marks a beat as late, x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar.

The Wispy Lyrics is a form of music used during marches and military engagements originating in The Meandering Confederacy. The rules of the form are applied by composers to produce individual pieces of music which can be performed. A singer recites any composition of The Convenient Chips while the music is played on a enthep and three duka. The musical voices cover melody, harmony and rhythm. The entire performance is consistently slowing. The melody has long phrases throughout the form. It is performed using the nithros scale. Throughout, when possible, composers and performers are to play arpeggios and spread syllables over many notes. [B]The singer always should be fiery. [B]The enthep always should feel mysterious. [B]Each duka always should perform with a light touch. [B]The Wispy Lyrics has the following structure: a theme and one to two series of variations on the theme possibly all repeated. [B]The theme is voiced by the melody of the enthep, the rhythm of the singer and the rhythm of the duka. The passage is to be moderately soft. The enthep stays in the buzzy low register and the singer's voice covers its entire range. This passage features only melodic tones and intervals. The passage is performed in the bepa rhythm. The passage should be composed and performed using syncopation and legato. [B]Each of the series of variations is voiced by the melody of the singer and the harmony of the enthep. Each passage is to be very soft. The singer's voice stays in the high register and the enthep covers its entire range from the buzzy low register to the strident high register. Only one pitch is ever played at a time in this passage. Each passage is performed in the umac rhythm. Each passage should be composed and performed using legato. [B]Scales are conceived of as two chords built using a division of the perfect fourth interval into eight notes. The tonic note is a fixed tone passed from teacher to student. Every note is named. The names are stalcon (spoken sta), nek (ne), lastta (la), cish (ci), ani (an), shato (sha), almef (al) and onod (on). [B]As always, the nithros hexatonic scale is thought of as two disjoint chords drawn from the fundamental division of the perfect fourth. These chords are named agtha and othag. [B]The agtha tetrachord is the 1st, the 2nd, the 3rd and the 8th degrees of the fundamental perfect fourth division. [B]The othag trichord is the 1st, the 5th and the 8th degrees of the fundamental perfect fourth division. [B]The rhythm system is fundamentally polyrhythmic. There are always multiple rhythm lines, and each of their bars is played over the same period of time, regardless of the number of beats. The rhythm lines are thought of as one, without a primary-subordinate relationship, though individual lines can be named. [B]The bepa rhythm is a single line with thirty-two beats divided into eight bars in a 4-4-4-4-4-4-4-4 pattern. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x - - x | - - - x | - x X x | x x - X | X - x x | - x x - | x - - - | - - - x | [B]where X marks an accented beat, x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The umac rhythm is made from two patterns: the cadem (considered the primary) and the osp. As stated above, they are to be played in polyrhythm. [B]The cadem rhythm is a single line with four beats. The beats are named caquot (spoken ca), shibbi (shi), aro (ar) and stral (stra). The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| X - x x | [B]where X marks an accented beat, x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The osp rhythm is a single line with three beats. The beats are named arin (spoken ar), umo (um) and rostfen (ro). The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x x X | [B]where X marks an accented beat, x is a beat and | indicates a bar.

The Scintillating Songs is a form of music used to commemorate important events originating in The Meandering Confederacy. The form guides musicians during improvised performances. The music is played on a enthep. The entire performance is very fast, and it is to be very loud. The melody has phrases of varied length throughout the form. Only one pitch is ever played at a time. It is performed using the tunem scale and in the thothil rhythm. Throughout, when possible, performers are to play rapid runs, modulate frequently and freely adjust the beats. [B]The enthep always does the main melody and should be merry. [B]The Scintillating Songs has a well-defined multi-passage structure: a lengthy introduction, a verse and a chorus all repeated one times and a finale. [B]In the introduction, the enthep covers its entire range from the buzzy low register to the strident high register. [B]In the verse, the enthep ranges from the raucous middle register to the strident high register. [B]In the chorus, the enthep stays in the buzzy low register. The passage should be performed using staccato. [B]In the finale, the enthep stays in the raucous middle register. [B]Scales are conceived of as two chords built using a division of the perfect fourth interval into eight notes. The tonic note is a fixed tone passed from teacher to student. Every note is named. The names are stalcon (spoken sta), nek (ne), lastta (la), cish (ci), ani (an), shato (sha), almef (al) and onod (on). [B]As always, the tunem hexatonic scale is thought of as two disjoint chords drawn from the fundamental division of the perfect fourth. These chords are named agtha and dik. [B]The agtha tetrachord is the 1st, the 2nd, the 3rd and the 8th degrees of the fundamental perfect fourth division. [B]The dik trichord is the 1st, the 2nd and the 8th degrees of the fundamental perfect fourth division. [B]The rhythm system is fundamentally polyrhythmic. There are always multiple rhythm lines, and each of their bars is played over the same period of time, regardless of the number of beats. The rhythm lines are thought of as one, without a primary-subordinate relationship, though individual lines can be named. [B]The thothil rhythm is made from three patterns: the bepa (considered the primary), the apu and the tikbo. As stated above, they are to be played in polyrhythm. [B]The bepa rhythm is a single line with thirty-two beats divided into eight bars in a 4-4-4-4-4-4-4-4 pattern. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x - - x | - - - x | - x X x | x x - X | X - x x | - x x - | x - - - | - - - x | [B]where X marks an accented beat, x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The apu rhythm is a single line with three beats. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| - x - | [B]where x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The tikbo rhythm is a single line with twenty-three beats divided into two bars in a 6-17 pattern. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| - x - - x - | x - x X - - x x x - x - - - x x'- | [B]where X marks an accented beat, ' marks a beat as late, x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar.

The Veneration of Adoring is a form of music used during marches and military engagements originating in The Meandering Confederacy. The rules of the form are applied by composers to produce individual pieces of music which can be performed. The music is played on two nelti, a ubteng, a thogsloc and a ero. The musical voices join in melody, counterpoint and harmony. The entire performance should be graceful. The melody and counterpoint both have phrases of varied length throughout the form. It is performed without preference for a scale and in the sodu rhythm. Throughout, when possible, composers and performers are to glide from note to note and locally improvise. [B]Each nelti always does harmony. [B]The ubteng always does the main melody and plays arpeggios. [B]The thogsloc always does the main melody. The voice stays in the vibrating low register. [B]The ero always does the counterpoint melody. [B]The Veneration of Adoring has the following structure: a theme and one to two series of variations on the theme. [B]The theme is slow, and it is to be very soft. The ubteng ranges from the heavy low register to the vibrating high register, the thogsloc stays in the vibrating low register and the ero ranges from the slicing low register to the dark middle register. This passage features only melodic tones and intervals. [B]Each of the series of variations is extremely fast, and it is to be soft. The ubteng covers its entire range from the heavy low register to the vibrating top register, the thogsloc stays in the vibrating low register and the ero ranges from the dark middle register to the wispy high register. This passage is richly layered with full chords making use of the available range. [B]The rhythm system is fundamentally polyrhythmic. There are always multiple rhythm lines, and each of their bars is played over the same period of time, regardless of the number of beats. The rhythm lines are thought of as one, without a primary-subordinate relationship, though individual lines can be named. [B]The sodu rhythm is made from two patterns: the apu (considered the primary) and the osp. [B]The apu rhythm is a single line with three beats. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| - x - | [B]where x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The osp rhythm is a single line with three beats. The beats are named arin (spoken ar), umo (um) and rostfen (ro). The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x x X | [B]where X marks an accented beat, x is a beat and | indicates a bar.

dance_form.description: The Silks of Glitter is a group performance dance originating in The Rack of Murdering. The form guides dancers during improvised performances. The dance is accompanied by any composition of The Zephyr of Berries. The dancers perform in several lines along an intricate path. The debauched energetic dance is punctuated by independent body movement and leaps. [B]The dance begins with the passage of the music. The dancers perform very slowly to the biban rhythm. This section is punctuated by straight-lined raised left arms and straight-lined hand gestures, with large moves. [B]The dance enters a new section with the next passage of the music. The dancers perform faster and faster to the roder rhythm. This powerful section is punctuated by proud sway.

The Beloved Poet is a social partner dance originating in The Rack of Murdering. The form guides dancers during improvised performances. The dance is accompanied by The Fortuitous Suitor. The dancers perform in a single line, moving very slowly with the music. The partners maintain open contact, communicating intent through touch. The dance is passionate and expressive. [B]The dance begins with the first theme of the music. This joyous vivacious section is punctuated by spirited facial expressions and right leg lifts. [B]The dance enters a new section with the exposition of the first theme of the music. The dancers perform to the lakish rhythm. This vivacious section is punctuated by the high body level of the follower and leg lifts. [B]The dance enters a new section with the second theme of the music. The dancers perform to the gostang rhythm. There are partner changes with the lead turning out counterclockwise. [B]The dance enters a new section with the exposition of the second theme of the music. There are partner changes with the lead turning out clockwise. This strong sensual section is punctuated by proud leftward bends, right leg lifts and the lively independent body movement of the lead. [B]The dance enters a new section with the bridge-passage of the music. The dancers perform to the libash rhythm. There are partner changes with the lead turning out clockwise. This section is punctuated by the raised left arms of the follower, the raised right arms of the follower and joyous footwork. [B]The dance enters a new section with the synthesis of the music. The dancers perform to the nel rhythm. There are partner changes with the lead turning out clockwise. This section is intense.

The Velvety Satin is a performance partner dance originating in The Rack of Murdering. The form guides dancers during improvised performances. The dance is accompanied by The Fortuitous Suitor. The dancers perform in several lines, moving very slowly with the music. The partners rarely make contact, communicating intent briefly through spoken cues. This dance is a refined artform, with ten specific moves to be mastered. The lively dance is punctuated by the large leaps of the lead, sinuous hand gestures and elaborate body level changes. [B]The dance begins with the first theme of the music. This proud aggressive sprightly section is punctuated by the high right leg lifts of the follower, the runs of the follower and the independent body movement of the follower. [B]The dance enters a new section with the exposition of the first theme of the music. The dancers perform to the lakish rhythm. This section is straight-lined. [B]The dance enters a new section with the second theme of the music. The dancers perform to the gostang rhythm. This section is punctuated by vigorous curved walks and energetic spins. [B]The dance enters a new section with the exposition of the second theme of the music. This strong jerking section is punctuated by large moves. [B]The dance enters a new section with the bridge-passage of the music. The dancers perform to the libash rhythm. This section is twisting and debauched. [B]The dance enters a new section with the synthesis of the music. The dancers perform to the nel rhythm. This debauched section is punctuated by the counterclockwise eighth turns of the lead. [B]The ugog is one of the fundamental dance moves. There is a spin from the follower with a body level change and a twisting raised left arm from the follower. [B]The ish is one of the fundamental dance moves. There is a loudly percussive leap from the lead with a low right kick and independent body movement. [B]The robek is one of the fundamental dance moves. First, there is a sinuous leap from the lead. Then there is a powerful spin from the follower with a high left leg lift. Finally, there is a straight-lined right kick. [B]The olmul is one of the fundamental dance moves. There is a spirited leap with a proud arm carriage from the lead, a spirited clockwise eighth turn from the lead and a sinuous hand gesture from the follower. [B]The nokzam is one of the fundamental dance moves. There is fluid footwork from the lead with a raised right arm. [B]The emuth is one of the fundamental dance moves. There is a leg lift from the follower. [B]The fer is one of the fundamental dance moves. There is a jerking kick from the follower. [B]The uvel is one of the fundamental dance moves. There is a softly percussive leap with a flamboyant hand gesture, a debauched arm carriage from the follower and a flamboyant counterclockwise eighth half turn. [B]The dolush is one of the fundamental dance moves. There is a refined spin with a leap. [B]The agek is one of the fundamental dance moves. First, there is a proud spin. Then there is sensual footwork with a grotesque hand gesture. Then there is an intense raised right arm with debauched independent body movement and a graceful leap from the lead. Finally, there is an intense raised right arm with a low leap from the follower, an expressive spin and a debauched facial expression from the follower.

The Tresses of Luxury is a social partner dance originating in The Buff Satins. The form guides dancers during improvised performances. The dance is accompanied by any composition of The Velvety Music. The dancers perform loosely mingled, moving to the music's cenopu rhythm. The partners maintain open contact, communicating intent by pulling away briefly. The entire dance has a basic movement called the alo. There is a series of two steps in a figure-eight pattern with a joyous facial expression from the follower and a low body level. The dance is spirited and proud. [B]The dance begins with the chorus of the music. The dancers perform slower and slower with the music. This aggressive section is punctuated by independent body movement, jerking footwork and elaborate sway. [B]The dance enters a new section with the verse of the music. The dancers perform quickly with the music. This section is punctuated by grotesque footwork and independent body movement. [B]The dance enters a new section with the bridge-passage of the music. The dancers perform very quickly with the music. This section is passionate. [B]The dance enters a new section with the next chorus of the music. This section is punctuated by debauched leg lifts, vivacious leaps and the twisting footwork of the lead. [B]The dance enters a new section with the next verse of the music. The dancers perform quickly with the music. This expressive section is punctuated by lively leaps and the twisting kicks of the lead.

The Tenebrous Saturninity is a war dance originating in The Buff Satins. The form guides dancers during improvised performances. The dance is accompanied by any composition of The Flower of Tones. The dancers perform loosely mingled, moving slowly with the music. The dance is punctuated by spirited independent body movement and powerful leaps. [B]The dance begins with the verse of the music. The dancers perform turning counterclockwise. This section is punctuated by twisting counterclockwise eighth turns. [B]The dance enters a new section with the chorus of the music. This section is punctuated by relaxed hand gestures. [B]The dance enters a new section with the bridge-passage of the music. This intense section is punctuated by grotesque body level changes and raised left arms. [B]The dance enters a new section with the next verse of the music. The dancers perform turning counterclockwise. This section is sprightly. [B]The dance enters a new section with the next chorus of the music. The dancers perform along an improvised path.
